 <br>
As an example my father's(note: before people question my age because of this, keep in mind my parents are senior citizen and retired before you do age assumptions =P) website he owns(mainly maintained by others, I know more HTML than him and you can tell my internet knowledge beyond that is lacking), has a little IP log built into the page by the original designers of the site, no special HTML code I can find anywhere to make it work, just a little log file made in /LOG/XX-XX-XX each day after someone accesses the site. As I said I didn't do the page myself so who knows, but as far as him and I can tell, it's how the server itself automatically handles incoming IP's. Now, this being noted, breaking it down to which portion of the page they go to gets quite annoying in the log file, it tracks the directories a user accesses, but it's all sorted by time first, then by user name, so would take eons to sort and resort it without writing a program to do just that. So maybe it's something along that lines they do, and with say 400 people using the calendars.net, they don't feel like sorting out all the inappropriate IP's to send out their logs, as an example.<br>
